      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) below 5% for hemolysis index QoI at the nominal adult operating point.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study (6.2 M, 12.8 M, 25.4 M cells) performed at 4.5 L/min, 3 000 RPM. GCI for NIH = 3.1%. Extrapolated value used in validation comparison. Study conducted within adult flow envelope only; GCI at pediatric flow conditions not assessed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions match simulation inlet/outlet conditions within 2% for flow rate and within 50 RPM for rotational speed.",
      "rationale": "Ultrasonic flow meter (±1.5% FS) and optical encoder (±10 RPM) used during in-vitro testing. Boundary condition fidelity confirmed for all five adult validation points. Pediatric flow-rate range was not part of the experimental matrix at the time of validation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH within ±15% of measured NIH at all validation operating points; PIV velocity magnitude RMS error below 10%.",
      "rationale": "RH predictions at five adult operating points ranged from −4% to +12% relative to measured NIH. PIV RMS error 7.8%. Both criteria satisfied. Validation dataset frozen November–December 2022 and predates the Q3 2023 pediatric indication expansion. The assessment team asserts that model accuracy is expected to be maintained at lower flow rates based on dimensional similarity arguments, though no confirmatory test points exist."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to the clinical risk metric; scalar hemolysis power-law integrated along pathlines is the accepted surrogate.",
      "rationale": "RH computed via Lagrangian pathline integration using the Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law (C=3.62×10⁻⁵, α=2.416, β=0.785). This formulation is the accepted FDA-recognized surrogate for pump-induced hemolysis. The power-law coefficients were derived from adult erythrocyte shear-exposure data; applicability to neonatal or pediatric erythrocytes, which differ in membrane deformability, has not been independently verified within this assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities span the COU operating envelope in terms of flow rate, rotational speed, and fluid properties.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities covered 3.0–6.0 L/min and 2 400–3 600 RPM using ovine blood analog (glycerol–water, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s). These conditions are representative of the original adult COU. The pediatric sub-population (0.8–2.5 L/min, up to 4 200 RPM) was added to the cleared indication in Q3 2023 after the validation campaign was closed. The assessment team considers the existing validation envelope sufficient on the basis that turbulent flow similarity is maintained across the extended speed range; however, no validation test points at pediatric conditions are linked to this package, and no re-calibration or supplemental validation study has been initiated."
    },
    {
